## Normalised Extract

### String Creation and Type Distinctions

JavaScript supports two forms of strings: primitive strings and String objects.

String primitives created through:
- String literals with single or double quotes
- Template literals with backticks for interpolation
- String() function calls without new keyword
- Type coercion from other primitive types

String objects created through:
- String constructor with new keyword
- Wrapping primitive strings in object form

### Character Access Methods

Two approaches for accessing individual characters:

charAt() method provides safe character access:
- Returns character at specified index
- Returns empty string for out-of-bounds indices
- Accepts numeric index parameter

Bracket notation treats strings as array-like objects:
- Direct index access using square brackets
- Returns undefined for out-of-bounds indices  
- Read-only property access pattern

### String Comparison Operations

Standard comparison operators work with strings:
- Less-than and greater-than operators for lexicographic comparison
- Strict equality (===) and loose equality (==) for exact matching
- All string comparisons are case-sensitive by default

Case-insensitive comparison requires normalization:
- toUpperCase() or toLowerCase() methods for conversion
- Locale-aware comparison using localeCompare() method
- Intl.Collator API for advanced internationalization needs

### String Coercion and Type Conversion

Built-in operations automatically convert values to strings:
- undefined converts to "undefined"  
- null converts to "null"
- Boolean true converts to "true", false to "false"
- Numbers convert to decimal representation
- Objects call toString() method for conversion

### Concatenation and Building Patterns

Multiple approaches for combining strings:
- Plus operator (+) for simple concatenation
- Template literals for interpolation and multi-line strings
- Array join() method for efficient multiple string combination
- String concatenation assignment operator (+=) for accumulation

### Internationalization Support

Locale-aware string operations through:
- localeCompare() method for culture-specific comparison
- Intl.Collator for advanced collation and sorting
- toLocaleLowerCase() and toLocaleUpperCase() for locale-specific case conversion
- Sensitivity options for accent and case handling

### Performance Considerations

String immutability affects performance patterns:
- String operations create new string instances
- Repeated concatenation creates multiple temporary strings
- Array join() more efficient for building large strings from parts
- Template literals optimized for interpolation scenarios

## Supplementary Details

JavaScript string handling integrates primitive and object semantics through automatic boxing, allowing method calls on primitive string values. The language provides comprehensive Unicode support with proper handling of multi-byte character sequences.

String methods generally return new string instances rather than modifying existing strings, following functional programming patterns that avoid mutation of primitive values.

## Reference Details

### String Creation Patterns
```javascript
// Primitive strings  
const str1 = "literal string";
const str2 = 'single quotes';  
const str3 = `template literal`;
const str4 = String(123);

// String objects
const strObj = new String("object string");
```

### Character Access Methods
```javascript
// charAt() method
"example".charAt(0);     // "e"
"example".charAt(10);    // ""

// Bracket notation
"example"[0];           // "e"  
"example"[10];          // undefined
```

### Type Checking Patterns
```javascript
// Primitive vs object detection
typeof "string";              // "string"
typeof new String("string");  // "object"

// String detection
const isString = value => typeof value === 'string';
const isStringLike = value => typeof value === 'string' || 
                             value instanceof String;
```

### Comparison Operations
```javascript
// Basic comparison
"apple" < "banana";           // true
"Apple" < "apple";            // true (A < a)

// Case-insensitive comparison
function compareIgnoreCase(a, b) {
  return a.toLowerCase() === b.toLowerCase();
}

// Locale-aware comparison  
"Äpfel".localeCompare("Zebra", "de", { sensitivity: 'base' });
```

### String Coercion Examples
```javascript
// Automatic coercion
String(undefined);    // "undefined"
String(null);         // "null"  
String(true);         // "true"
String(123);          // "123"
String([1, 2, 3]);    // "1,2,3"

// Explicit conversion
(123).toString();     // "123"
true.toString();      // "true"
```

### Concatenation Patterns
```javascript
// Plus operator
const result = "Hello" + " " + "World";

// Template literals
const name = "Alice";
const greeting = `Hello, ${name}!`;

// Array join for multiple strings
const parts = ["one", "two", "three"];
const combined = parts.join(" ");

// Accumulation pattern
let output = "";
for (const item of items) {
  output += item + "\n";
}
```

### Internationalization Patterns
```javascript
// Locale comparison
"café".localeCompare("cafe", "en", { sensitivity: 'accent' });

// Case conversion with locale
"İstanbul".toLocaleLowerCase("tr");  // "istanbul"  
"İstanbul".toLocaleLowerCase("en");  // "i̇stanbul"

// Collation configuration
const collator = new Intl.Collator('de', {
  sensitivity: 'base',
  caseFirst: 'upper'
});
```

### Performance Optimization Patterns  
```javascript
// Inefficient repeated concatenation
let result = "";
for (let i = 0; i < items.length; i++) {
  result += items[i];  // Creates new string each iteration
}

// Efficient array join approach
const parts = [];
for (let i = 0; i < items.length; i++) {
  parts.push(items[i]);
}
const result = parts.join("");
```

### String Validation Patterns
```javascript
// Length validation
function validateLength(str, max) {
  return typeof str === 'string' && str.length <= max;
}

// Format validation  
function isEmail(str) {
  return typeof str === 'string' && /\S+@\S+\.\S+/.test(str);
}
```

### Unicode Handling
```javascript
// Proper Unicode iteration
for (const char of "👋🌍") {
  console.log(char);  // Handles multi-byte characters correctly
}

// Character counting
function countCharacters(str) {
  return [...str].length;  // Unicode-aware counting
}
```

